ercy (1599\u20131660), daughter of [[Henry Percy, 9th Earl of Northumberland]] (the famous \"Wizard Earl\"), by his wife [[Dorothy Percy, Countess of Northumberland|Dorothy Devereux]].{{sfn|Chisholm|1911|p=339}}\n\n[[File:Coat of arms of Sir James Hay, 1st Earl of Carlisle, KG.png|thumb|left|Coat of arms of Sir James Hay, 1st Earl of Carlisle, KG]]\nIn 1618 he resigned the mastership of the wardrobe for a large sum in compensation. He was created Viscount Doncaster, and in February 1619 was despatched on a mission to [[Kingdom of Germany|Germany]], where during the beginning [[Thirty Years' War]] he identified himself with the cause of the \"Winter King\", Elector [[Frederick V of the Palatinate]], and urged James to make war in his support. In 1621 and 1622 he was sent to [[Kingdom of France|France]] to obtain peace for the [[Huguenots]] from [[Louis XIII of France|Louis XIII]], in which he was unsuccessful, and in September 1622 was created [[Earl of Carlisle]].{{sfn|Chisholm|1911|p=339}}\n\nNext year he went to [[Paris]] on the occasion of Prince Charles's journey to [[Madrid]], and again in 1624 to join [[Henry Rich, 1st Earl of Holland|Henry Rich]], afterwards Lord Holland, in negotiating the prince's marriage with [[Henrietta Maria]], when he advised James without success to resist [[Cardinal Richelieu|Richelieu]]'s demands on the subject of religious toleration.{{sfn|Chisholm|1911|p=339}} In 1624 he was made a knight of the [[Order of the Garter]]. Charles's marriage in 1625 was [[Proxy marriage|by proxy]], so the wedding contract was signed by Carlisle and Holland. The king's representative at the actual wedding was [[Claude de Lorraine, Duke of Chevreuse|the duke of Chevreuse]], yet Carlisle and Holland acted as witnesses.{{Citation needed|date=April 2019}}\n\nCarlisle became gentleman of the bedchamber to [[Charles I of England|King Charles I]] after his accession. In 1628, after the failure of the expedition to [[Isle of Rhe|Rhe]], he was sent to make a diversion against [[Cardinal Richelieu]] in [[Lorraine (province)|Lorraine]] and [[Piedmont (Italy)|Piedmont]]; he counselled peace with Spain and the vigorous prosecution of the war with France, but on his return home found his advice neglected. He took no further part in public life, and died in March 1636.{{sfn|Chisholm|1911|pp=339\u2013340}}\n\nCarlisle was a man of good sense and of accommodating temper, with some diplomatic ability. His extravagance and lavish expenditure, his double suppers and costly entertainments, were the theme of satirists and wonder of society, and his debts were said at his death to amount to more than \u00a380,000. He left behind him, says [[Edward Hyde, 1st Earl of Clarendon|Clarendon]], a reputation of a very fine gentleman and a most accomplished courtier, and after having spent, in a very jovial life, above \u00a3400,000, which upon a strict computation he received from the crown, he left not a house or acre of land to be remembered by.{{sfn|Chisholm|1911|p=340}}\n\n==Colonial proprietor==\nHay by 1612 was a director of the [[Virginia Company]].<ref>Schreiber, p. 168.</ref> He was a patentee and councillor of the plantation of [[New England]], and showed great interest in the colonies.{{sfn|Chisholm|1911|p=339}}\n\nCarlise also had an interest in the Caribbean. There [[James Ley, 1st Earl of Marlborough]] was a rival, who had to be bought off.<ref>Schreiber, p. 170.</ref> Another rival was the [[Philip Herbert, 4th Earl of Pembroke|Earl of Montgomery]].<ref>{{cite ODNB|id=12723|title=Hay, James|first=Roy E.|last=Schreiber}}</ref> On 2 July 1627 Carlisle obtained from the king a [[Proprietary colony|grant]] of all the [[Caribbean Islands]], including [[Barbados]], this being a confirmation of a former concession given by [[James I of England|James I]].{{sfn|Chisholm|1911|p=339}} A colonial plantation venture on Barbados was led in 1628 by [[Marmaduke Roydon]], a prominent [[City of London]] merchant and one of Carlisle's major creditors.<ref>{{cite ODNB|id=24237|title=Roydon (Rawdon), Sir Marmaduke (1583\u20131646)|first=John C.|last=Appleby}}</ref>\n\n==Family==\nHay's first wife was Honoria Denny. His second wife, [[Lucy Hay, Countess of Carlisle]], was involved in many conspiracies, or allegations thereof, during the [[English Civil War]].{{sfn|Chisholm|1911|p=340}}\n\nThe first earl was succeeded by James, his only surviving son by his first wife.  James married Margaret Russell, third daughter of [[Francis Russell, 4th Earl of Bedford]], but James died without issue on 30 October 1660. At his death, the peerage became extinct in the Hay family.{{sfn|Chisholm|1911|p=340}} The Hay Family currently spans across the world.{{Citation needed|date=April 2019}}\n\n==References==\n*{{cite book |last1=Carrington |first1=Sean |last2=Fraser |first2=Henry |title=A~Z of Barbados Heritage |year=2003 |publisher=Macmillan Caribbean |isbn=978-0-333-92068-8 |pages=14, 29, 186 }}\n*Roy E. Schreiber, ''The First Carlisle Sir James Hay, First Earl of Carlisle as Courtier, Diplomat and Entrepreneur, 1580-1636'', Transactions of the American Philosophical Society New Series, Vol. 74, No. 7 (1984), pp.&nbsp;1\u2013202. Published by: American Philosophical Society. Stable URL: https://www.jstor.org/stable/1006420.\n*{{cite news |title=Bagatelle Great House, Restaurant and Wine Bar and Lord Willoughby's Tavern officially open |author=Staff writer |first= |last= |authorlink= |url=http://www.barbadosadvocate.com/NewViewNewsleft.cfm?Record=22775 |format= |agency= |newspaper=[[Barbados Advocate]] |publisher= |location= |isbn= |issn= |oclc= |pmid= |pmd= |bibcode= |doi= |id= |date=12 September 2005 |page= |pages= |at= |accessdate=4 June 2010 |trans-title=|quote= |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20051224054950/http://www.barbadosadvocate.com/NewViewNewsleft.cfm?Record=22775 |archivedate=24 December 2005 |ref= }}\n'''Attribution:'''\n* {{EB1911|wstitle=Carlisle, Earls of|volume=5|pages=339\u2013341}}\n\n==Notes==\n{